[Malkangiri district is the SW point of the state of Orissa and
distant in many ways from the state capital, Bhubaneswa; see:
http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/india_pol01.jpg
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malkangiri_district
For Malkangiri, go to:
http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/37/Malkangiri.html
http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/orissa/districts/malkangiri.htm.

Orissa was renamed Odisha on 5 Nov 2011.

In general the Indian tribal areas are poorly served by the state
veterinary services and thus situations can be well developed before a
response gets called in. Plus Orissa (for consistency I am using the
old name) has enzootic anthrax in 18/30 districts. In 2005 there were
a total of 6 outbreaks, all involving cattle (32 cases); 2006, 3
outbreaks and 23 cattle cases; 2007, 10 outbreaks with 65 cattle and 4
sheep/goats affected; 2008, 5 outbreaks with 56 cattle cases; 2009, 4
outbreaks and 36 cattle cases; and 2010, 10 outbreaks with 32 cattle
cases. A proactive control and surveillance programme would be more
cost effective than their present reactive response.

Our local members are asked to pass on any information concerning the
confirmation, or not, of bovine anthrax in these 8 villages. -
Mod.MHJ]
